const a = [
  {"id":614,"text":"A 35-year-old man with a history of intravenous (IV) drug abuse has generalized lymphadenopathy. Which of the following tests would help in finding the cause of his lymphadenopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 312. (2) Hematology module, Medicine lecture slides, Topic: Approach to a patient of lymphadenopathy with and without splenomegaly, Sub-topic: location.","responses":[{"text":"Histopathology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasonography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV serology","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count (CBC)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":653,"text":"A 65-year-old male presents with a 2-month history of fever and weight loss. On examination, the spleen is palpable 6 cm below the left costal margin. Complete blood count (CBC) reveals leukocytes=125x10⁹/L, hemoglobin=7.0 gm/dL and platelets= 510X10³/µL . He is diagnosed with chronic myeloid leukemia. Which of the following defects is present in chronic myeloid leukemia?","explanation":"The specific genetic defect associated with CML is the **t(9:22)** translocation, also known as the Philadelphia chromosome. This translocation results in the formation of the BCR-ABL fusion gene, which encodes a constitutively active tyrosine kinase. This abnormal kinase activity drives the uncontrolled proliferation of myeloid cells seen in CML.\r\n\r\nThe presence of the t(9:22) translocation is a hallmark of CML and is essential for its diagnosis. It is also a therapeutic target for drugs like tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs), such as imatinib, which have revolutionized the treatment of this leukemia.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 616.","responses":[{"text":"t(11:21)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"t(9:22)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"t(15:17)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"t(8:21)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"t(9:11)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":657,"text":"Putrefaction is said to be colliquative when there is which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow Lecture Slides Hematology module, Forensic Medicine lecture slides, Death I, \"Putrefaction.\"","responses":[{"text":"Swollen, puffy, bloated face","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colour change at right iliac fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Appearance of maggots","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Distention of abdominal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue conversion into solid mass","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":665,"text":"The process of decomposition in the air is twice as rapid as in water and eight times as rapid as in the soil this is called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Shedge R, Krishan K, Warrier V, Kanchan T. Postmortem Changes. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed March 31, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539741/","responses":[{"text":"Newton law","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Casper's dictum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Siphon principle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Locard's exchange principle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fudin's principle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":679,"text":"Which of the following is not correct about non-Hodgkin lymphoma?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Le, Tao, and Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 437. \r\n(2) Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 597, 603.","responses":[{"text":"Epstein-Barr virus is associated with post-transplant non-Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Males have a slightly higher risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Median age is 65-70 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burkitt lymphoma is most aggressive and incurable","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"t(14:18) in follicular lymphoma results in dysregulated BCL2 expression","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":705,"text":"A 45-year-old male who is bed-bound from paraplegia develops sudden shortness of breath. On examination, his right calf is found to be swollen and tender, a provisional diagnosis of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and pulmonary embolism is made. What will be the single most sought diagnostic test?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 697-698.\r\n\r\n2) Klok FA, Mos ICM, Kroft LJM, de Roos A, Huisman MV. Computed tomography pulmonary angiography as a single imaging test to rule out pulmonary embolism. Current Opinion in Pulmonary Medicine. Published September 2011. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21681098/","responses":[{"text":"Doppler venous ultrasonography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrocardiography (ECG)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray chest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography (CT) pulmonary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":766,"text":"Why is low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) preferred over unfractionated heparin (UFH)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 278.","responses":[{"text":"LMWH has lesser half life","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LMWH can be given in all conditions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LMWH has longer half life","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"LMWH has no side effects","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LMWH can be taken orally","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":770,"text":"Which of the following is the first immediate sign after death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Stiffening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary relaxation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigor mortis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Putrefaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary relaxation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":771,"text":"A guy who shoots himself tends to get instantaneous rigor instead of rigor mortis. Which one of the following statements most likely signifies the difference between the two?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 135.\r\n\r\n2)  Hematology module; Forensics medicine slides; Topic: Death-1; Sub-topic: Instantaneous rigor mortis (cadaveric spasm).","responses":[{"text":"Muscle contraction is less marked in instantaneous rigor mortis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Instantaneous rigor indicates time of death instead of mode of death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Instantaneous rigor affects all the muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary relaxation is absent in instantaneous rigor mortis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Instantaneous rigor mortis is not immediate after the death","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":772,"text":"A dead body is found by a group of people near the station. It is concluded that 6 to 10 hours have passed since the time of death. Which one of the following is most likely to be developed by this time in the body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 144.","responses":[{"text":"Postmortem lividity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Instantaneous rigor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium increase in CSF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Postmortem caloricity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigor mortis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":790,"text":"Which of the following is the most commonly encountered pattern of fingerprints?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accidental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loop","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Composite","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whorl","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":806,"text":"A 45-year-old male presents with a 2-month history of fever and weight loss. On examination, massive splenomegaly is observed. Complete blood count (CBC) reveals leukocyte count=165x10⁹/L, hemoglobin= 9.0 gm/dL and platelets=510 X10³/µL . He is diagnosed with chronic myeloid leukemia. Which of the following molecular defects is present in chronic myeloid leukemia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 616.","responses":[{"text":"BCL6 gene fusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"p53 gene mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RAR alpha (RARA) gene fusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BCR-ABL gene fusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"c-Myc gene fusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":833,"text":"For the purpose of determining age and sex from the skeleton of an unknown dead body, maximum information can be obtained by examining which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 64.","responses":[{"text":"Radius and ulna","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skull and mandible","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metacarpals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vertebrae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":834,"text":"A fresh victim of a road traffic accident is brought to the emergency department but lost his life on the\r\nway to the hospital. To confirm his death, the body is examined for all immediate signs of death. Which of\r\nthe following is an immediate sign of death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Awan NR. Principle and Practice Of Forensic Medicine. 2nd ed. Zubair Book Depot; 2018: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Postmortem lividity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary relaxation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Algor mortis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary relaxation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigor Mortis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":861,"text":"The dead body of a young female is recovered from her house hanging from a fan. On examination it is seen that post mortem lividity in lower limbs is fully developed and fixed. If, in the dead body, the post mortem lividity does not blanch on applying pressure, what will be the probable time elapsed since her death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 120, 154.","responses":[{"text":"0-3 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6-8 hours","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1-3 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3-6 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10-12 hours","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":883,"text":"A 10-year-old child with a known case of thalassemia major requires red cell transfusion every month, since the age of one year. For the last 5 to 6 months, he develops urticarial rashes during transfusion. What\r\nwill be an appropriate step for management?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 668.","responses":[{"text":"Transfuse washed red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transfuse Rh-negative blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prior to transfusion, give him one shot of steroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transfuse whole blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prior to transfusion, give him antihistamine and antipyretic drugs","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":885,"text":"A decapitated dead body of a male is brought for autopsy. What will be the most important part of an autopsy in this case for further identification?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Taking fingerprints of the body","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Preservation of 1st vertebra of the body distal to the cut","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taking bone marrow for DNA fingerprinting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taking poor prints","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taking photographs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":954,"text":"Which of the following is the surest sign to determine that hanging was ante-mortem, rather than post-mortem?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Cyanosis of face and lips","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligature around the neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperaemia of trachea and epiglottis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Protruding tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture of hyoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":982,"text":"A boy is convicted of a criminal offense and the judge of the juvenile court orders to send him to a reformatory school. This is because his age is less than which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 76.","responses":[{"text":"15 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"16 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"17 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"14 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"18 years","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1053,"text":"Different blood products are transfused in different clinical conditions. Which product is required if\r\na patient is bleeding actively and has deficiencies of multiple coagulation factors?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le, Tao, and Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Packed red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fresh frozen plasma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryoprecipitate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whole blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1055,"text":"Which of the following antibodies are present in Bernard-Soulier syndrome?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 434.","responses":[{"text":"Glycoprotein Ib/IIIb antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycoprotein IIa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycoprotein IIa/IIIb antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycoprotein Ib antibodies","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet membrane phospholipids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1108,"text":"A cord blood sample of an Rh-ve mother was sent for laboratory testing during labor. Which of the following would indicate the need for blood exchange transfusion?","explanation":null,"reference":"Goljan EF. Rapid Review Pathology. 5th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2019: 416.","responses":[{"text":"Peripheral cells shows spherocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect coombs test is weakly negative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin = 10 mg/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticulocyte is corrected to 7%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum bilirubin = 2.5 mg/dL","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1184,"text":"The postmortem sign of 'cattle trucking' is seen in which organ?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 137.","responses":[{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cornea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retina","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Limbs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1227,"text":"Which of the following is the result of vitamin B12 deficiency?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le, Tao, and Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 428.","responses":[{"text":"Impaired coagulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired hemoglobin synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired DNA synthesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematopoietic stem cell failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Impaired collagen formation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1233,"text":"A 29-year-old female comes for a routine checkup as part of a pre-employment requirement. Her complete blood count reveals Hb= 10 gm/dL with microcytic hypochromic red cell indices. Assuming that she is a carrier of the beta-thalassemia trait, what will be the most likely findings on her hemoglobin electrophoresis to confirm her carrier status?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 416, 641. \r\n\r\n(2) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 44.","responses":[{"text":"Normal HbA and A2, but markedly increased HbF (\u003e90%)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal HbA and A2, but slightly increased HbF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal HbA and increased Hb A2 (4-8%)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased HbA,and raised HbA2 and HbF","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal HbA and increased Hb A2 (3-5%)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1251,"text":"A detective is searching for evidence at a crime scene when he encounters fingerprints on the doorknob. He takes the impressions for examination. Inspection reveals that the pattern resembles hairpin heads that are elongated in the left direction. What is the most likely fingerprint pattern in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 85.\r\n2) D'24 slides; Hematology module, Forensic-medicine lecture slides, Topic: Personal identity III; Sub-topic: Various patterns seen in fingerprints.\r\n3) Fingerprint | definition \u0026 facts | britannica. Accessed March 31, 2022. https://www.britannica.com/topic/fingerprint","responses":[{"text":"Loop","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Composite","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tented arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Whorl","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1255,"text":"A young boy is arrested due to a criminal charge. The court orders for a detailed forensic examination to determine his age. Pelvic X-ray findings show that the ischium and pubis are not united. What is the approximate age of the boy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas, Gautam. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed., Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers, 2015: 72.","responses":[{"text":"25 years or more","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 25 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 7 years","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 12 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 18 years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1257,"text":"A 21-year-old female presents with petechiae on her skin and episodes of epistaxis for the last two months. On examination, there is no hepatosplenomegaly or lymphadenopathy. Which of the following is the most sensitive earliest test for making a diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 656, 657.","responses":[{"text":"Bone marrow aspiration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antinuclear antibody (ANA) profile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver function test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet count","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticulocyte count","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1267,"text":"The age of a young boy needs to be determined. Dental X-ray reveals mixed dentition and examination of the oral cavity reveals that the first molars have erupted. What is the approximate age of this boy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 69.","responses":[{"text":"16-18 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6-9 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5-7 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10-12 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6-7 years","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1268,"text":"The approximate age of a girl needs to be determined as ordered by the court. After getting a series of X-rays done, it is revealed that she has only 3 carpal bones ossified. What is the likely age of the girl?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas, Gautam. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed., Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers, 2015: 73.","responses":[{"text":"10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4014,"text":"A 5-year-old boy comes to the outpatient department complaining of a painful and swollen knee. On examination, bleeding is seen within the knee joint but with no signs of physical trauma. His mother gives a family history of a maternal uncle who recently died of a bleeding disorder. Investigations show isolated increased APTT. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hemophilia A** is an X-linked recessive disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of coagulation factor VIII.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of a painful and swollen joint without a history of physical trauma suggests an intra-articular hemorrhage. Hemophilia A leads to impaired blood clotting, specifically due to a deficiency of factor VIII, which is involved in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation. As a result, patients with hemophilia A are prone to prolonged APTT (activated partial thromboplastin time).\r\n\r\nThe X-linked inheritance pattern explains the family history of a maternal uncle with a bleeding disorder. Hemophilia A predominantly affects males, while females are usually carriers of the disease.\r\n\r\nConfirmatory laboratory tests may include specific assays to measure factor VIII activity or genetic testing to identify mutations in the factor VIII gene.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662-663.","responses":[{"text":"Hemolytic uremic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4509,"text":"A person undergoes ileal resection. After some days he develops weakness, shortness of breath, and anemia. Which anemia can it possibly be?","explanation":"After ileal resection, the absorption of vitamin B12 is impaired since the ileum is responsible for the absorption of this essential vitamin. Vitamin B12 is required for the synthesis of DNA and normal red blood cell maturation. Therefore, a deficiency of vitamin B12 leads to **megaloblastic anemia**.\r\n\r\nMegaloblastic anemia is characterized by the presence of large, immature red blood cells (megaloblasts) in the bone marrow. These cells have impaired DNA synthesis, leading to delayed maturation. The result is fewer and larger red blood cells in circulation.\r\n\r\nClinical manifestations of megaloblastic anemia include weakness, shortness of breath, and anemia symptoms due to decreased oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. Other symptoms may include pale skin, fatigue, and neurological manifestations such as numbness and tingling in the extremities.\r\n\r\nSupplementation of vitamin B12 is necessary to correct the deficiency and alleviate the symptoms of megaloblastic anemia.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 45.","responses":[{"text":"Chronic blood loss anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pernicious anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4521,"text":"Which interleukin is required for the growth and proliferation of all the stem cells?","explanation":"**Interleukin-3 (IL-3)** is a cytokine that plays a crucial role in the growth and proliferation of stem cells. IL-3 is produced by various cells, including activated T cells and mast cells, and acts on hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow. \r\n\r\nIL-3 stimulates the production and differentiation of multiple blood cell lineages, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. It acts as a growth factor for early progenitor cells, promoting their survival, proliferation, and differentiation into specific cell types. By supporting the growth of stem cells, IL-3 helps to maintain a healthy and functional hematopoietic system.\r\n\r\nWhile other interleukins, such as IL-1, IL-4, IL-5, and IL-2, also play important roles in immune regulation and hematopoiesis, IL-3 is specifically known for its broad effects on stem cell growth and proliferation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Interleukin-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-3","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10026,"text":"In case of an injury, a deficiency of which of the following would impair the adhesion of platelets to the subendothelial collagen?","explanation":"In the process of hemostasis, adhesion of platelets to the subendothelial collagen is a crucial step in forming a platelet plug to prevent bleeding. The key molecule involved in this adhesion is **von Willebrand factor (vWF)**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand factor is a multimeric glycoprotein synthesized by endothelial cells and megakaryocytes. It plays a critical role in mediating platelet adhesion by binding to both the exposed collagen at the site of injury and the platelet surface receptor, glycoprotein Ib (GPIb). This interaction between vWF and GPIb allows platelets to adhere to the damaged vessel wall and initiate the formation of a platelet plug.\r\n\r\nDeficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor can lead to a bleeding disorder known as von Willebrand disease, characterized by impaired platelet adhesion and defective clot formation. Without adequate von Willebrand factor, platelets are unable to adhere effectively to the subendothelial collagen, resulting in impaired hemostasis and prolonged bleeding.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinogen stabilizing factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand factor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10274,"text":"A 19-year-old girl presents to the office with non-tender, rubbery, enlarged cervical lymph nodes. She also has a low-grade fever and her complete blood count is normal. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hodgkin lymphoma** is characterized by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells within the lymph nodes. It often presents with painless, rubbery, and enlarged lymph nodes, typically in the neck (**cervical lymphadenopathy**), along with other symptoms like fever, night sweats, and weight loss. Importantly, individuals with Hodgkin lymphoma can have a **normal complete blood count**, which distinguishes it from some other lymphoproliferative disorders.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nNon-Hodgkin lymphoma can also present with lymphadenopathy but the clinical features of Hodgkin lymphoma such as the rubbery consistency of the enlarged lymph nodes and the demographic make it a more likely diagnosis in this case.\r\n\r\nTuberculoid lymphadenitis, while a possibility, would often be associated with a history of tuberculosis exposure or symptoms suggestive of active tuberculosis infection.\r\n\r\nAcute and chronic leukemias typically involve abnormalities in the complete blood count, such as leukocytosis or leukopenia, which are not mentioned in this case.","reference":"1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 962.\r\n\r\n2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 588.","responses":[{"text":"Acute leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculoid lymphadenitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10275,"text":"What is the composition of adult hemoglobin?","explanation":"**Hemoglobin A** (HbA) is the predominant type of hemoglobin in adult humans and is composed of **two alpha-globin chains** and **two beta-globin chains**. This composition allows HbA to effectively transport oxygen in the bloodstream. The other listed combinations represent different types of hemoglobin, but HbA is the primary hemoglobin found in adult red blood cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAlpha 2, delta 2 represents hemoglobin A2 (HbA2).\r\n\r\nAlpha 2, epsilon 2 represents hemoglobin E (HbE).\r\n\r\nAlpha 2, gamma 2 represents hemoglobin F (HbF), also known as fetal hemoglobin. \r\n\r\nZeta 2, epsilon 2 represents hemoglobin Gower 2 (HbGower 2).","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 414.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha 2, beta 2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha 2, delta 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha 2, epsilon 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zeta 2, epsilon 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha 2, gamma 2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10276,"text":"Where will hypostasis be seen in a body drowned in running water?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 144.","responses":[{"text":"Dependant part of upper limbs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower limbs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No lividity will be seen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Front of the nose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10278,"text":"Which of these factors can lead to poor tissue oxygenation?","explanation":"Insufficient or **impaired blood flow** to tissues can result in **poor oxygen delivery** to cells. Conditions such as vascular diseases, embolism, or severe hypotension can reduce blood flow and compromise tissue oxygenation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nA right shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve is a consequence of the decreased affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen. However, it does not explain the underlying cause.\r\n\r\nAn increased blood volume, as seen in conditions like polycythemia or fluid overload, can potentially improve tissue oxygenation by increasing the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood.\r\n\r\nPolycythemia, characterized by an increase in red blood cell mass, can potentially improve tissue oxygenation by increasing the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. \r\n\r\nAn increase in hemoglobin levels can enhance the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood and may improve tissue oxygenation.","reference":"Bhutta BS, Alghoula F, Berim I. Hypoxia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 1, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482316/","responses":[{"text":"Polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right shift of hemoglobin curve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Poor blood flow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased blood volume","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10279,"text":"Which of these terms best explain the pancytopenia observed in aplastic anemia?","explanation":"**Aplastic anemia** is a condition characterized by **bone marrow failure**, where the bone marrow does not produce an adequate number of red blood cells (anemia), white blood cells (leukopenia), and platelets (thrombocytopenia). This failure of the bone marrow to produce sufficient blood cells is the primary reason for the **pancytopenia** seen in aplastic anemia.","reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 653.\r\n\r\n2) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 51.","responses":[{"text":"Splenomegaly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immunodeficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neoplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10281,"text":"An 11-year-old girl presents with a petechial rash all over her body. Her bleeding time and activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT) are prolonged but the prothrombin time (PT) is normal. Her sister also suffers from a similar condition. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Von Willebrand disease** (VWD) is a hereditary bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor (vWF), a protein that plays a crucial role in platelet adhesion and clot formation. It can lead to prolonged bleeding times and a tendency to develop mucocutaneous bleeding symptoms, such as petechiae and ecchymoses.\r\n\r\nIn VWD, the **aPTT** is often **prolonged** due to the role of vWF in stabilizing factor VIII. However, the **PT** remains **normal** because the extrinsic pathway of coagulation, which is assessed by the PT, is typically unaffected.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP) typically presents with microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, and neurological symptoms, which are not mentioned in this case.\r\n\r\nImmune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is characterized by isolated thrombocytopenia without a prolonged aPTT or PT.\r\n\r\nAcute leukemia may present with bleeding symptoms, but it is usually associated with significant abnormalities in the complete blood count (CBC) and peripheral blood smear.\r\n\r\nHemophilia primarily affects factor VIII (in hemophilia A) or factor IX (in hemophilia B) and is associated with aPTT prolongation. However, it is less likely in this case due to the presence of a normal PT and a family history more consistent with VWD.","reference":"1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 34.\r\n\r\n2) Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 437.","responses":[{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10282,"text":"Which of the following chromosomes contain the gene for the beta-globin chain of hemoglobin?","explanation":"The HBB gene, which codes for the **beta-globin** chain of hemoglobin, is found on the short arm of **chromosome 11** (11p15.5). Mutations in this gene can result in various beta-thalassemia syndromes, depending on the nature and severity of the mutation.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 428.","responses":[{"text":"11","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"14","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"16","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"9","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10283,"text":"Which of the following genotypes correctly correspond to the silent carrier state of alpha thalassemia?","explanation":"In the **silent carrier** state of **alpha thalassemia**, one of the four alpha-globin genes is deleted (–) on one chromosome, and the other three alpha-globin genes (α α) are present on the other chromosome. This results in reduced alpha-globin chain production but is generally clinically silent or asymptomatic (**α α/α –**).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n– –/– α represents a double gene deletion (– –) on one chromosome and an alpha gene (α) on the other chromosome, which is seen in hemoglobin H disease.\r\n\r\nα α/– – represents a genotype with two copies of alpha genes (α α) on one chromosome and double gene deletions (– –) on the other chromosome.\r\n\r\nαα/αα represents the normal genotype with two copies of alpha genes (α α) on both chromosomes.\r\n\r\nα –/α – represents a genotype with a single gene deletion (α –) on both chromosomes and is associated with the alpha thalassemia trait.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 428.","responses":[{"text":"– –/– α","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"αα/αα","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α α/α –","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"α –/α –","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α α/– –","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10284,"text":"Which type of hemolysis characterizes paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH)?","explanation":"**Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria** (PNH) is characterized by the destruction of red blood cells through **intravascular hemolysis**. In PNH, red blood cells are deficient in certain proteins that normally protect them from the complement system, a part of the immune system. Without this protection, the complement system can attack and destroy these cells within the blood vessels.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSplenic hemolysis and extravascular hemolysis refer to the destruction of red blood cells in the spleen or other parts of the reticuloendothelial system, not primarily seen in PNH.\r\n\r\nIntramedullary hemolysis occurs within the bone marrow when red blood cells are destroyed before they enter circulation.\r\n\r\nWhile extravascular hemolysis can occur to some extent in PNH, the hallmark and dominant type of hemolysis in this condition is intravascular.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 642.","responses":[{"text":"Both intra and extravascular hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravascular hemolysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extravascular hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramedullary hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10285,"text":"A 16-year-old boy, known case of hemophilia, injures himself while playing football and develops hemarthrosis in his right knee. What is the best treatment option?","explanation":"Hemophilia, particularly hemophilia A, is characterized by a deficiency of clotting factor VIII. When a patient with hemophilia A suffers from a bleeding episode, such as hemarthrosis (bleeding into a joint), the primary treatment is the replacement of the deficient clotting factor.\r\n\r\n**Recombinant factor 8** is the first-line treatment for hemarthrosis in hemophilia A patients. It directly addresses the underlying cause of bleeding by replacing the deficient factor VIII. Additionally, supportive measures like **bed rest** and **joint splinting** can help manage symptoms and prevent further joint damage.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile fresh frozen plasma (FFP) contains clotting factors, including factor VIII, it is not the preferred treatment for hemophilia A due to the lower concentration of factor VIII and the higher volume of fluid required, which can be burdensome for the patient.\r\n\r\nTranexamic acid is an antifibrinolytic agent that helps prevent clots from breaking down. While it can be used as an adjunct in treating bleeding in hemophilia, it does not replace the need for factor VIII in acute bleeding episodes.\r\n\r\nVitamin K is used to treat bleeding caused by vitamin K deficiency and in cases of warfarin overdose. It has no role in the treatment of hemophilia, which is a genetic deficiency of clotting factors.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 972.","responses":[{"text":"Recombinant factor 8 + bed rest + splint","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fresh frozen plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Injection of Vitamin K","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recombinant factor 8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tranexamic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10286,"text":"Which of these indices is best for determining the race of a person?","explanation":"The **cephalic index** is a measurement of the head and is used to **determine race** on the ratio of the width to the length of the head (breadth divided by length times 100).\r\n\r\nDifferent racial and ethnic groups tend to have characteristic cephalic indices, categorized broadly into dolichocephalic (long and narrow head), mesocephalic (intermediate dimensions), and brachycephalic (short and broad head).\r\n\r\nThis index, while having its limitations and variations, is often used in anthropological studies to make inferences about the ancestry of skeletal remains.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe medullary index of hair measures the diameter of the hair medulla relative to the diameter of the hair shaft. While it can help distinguish between human and animal hair, it is not a reliable indicator of race.\r\n\r\nHumero-femoral index is the ratio of the length of the humerus to the length of the femur. It is more useful in determining differences in limb proportions, which can vary due to environmental adaptations rather than race.\r\n\r\nThe interfemoral index, calculated based on the relative lengths of the arms and legs, is used to study primate locomotion.\r\n\r\nThe ischiopubic index pertains to the pelvis and can be useful in sex determination rather than race.","reference":"1) Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 77.\r\n\r\n2) Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 57.","responses":[{"text":"Ischiopubic index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermembral index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medullary index of hair","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cephalic index","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Humero-femoral index","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10306,"text":"What do flow cytometry results show in paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria?","explanation":"**Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria** (PNH) is a rare acquired disorder characterized by the clonal expansion of hematopoietic stem cells that are deficient in glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI) anchors. This deficiency leads to the absence of certain GPI-anchored proteins on the surface of blood cells, most notably CD55 and CD59, which are crucial in protecting red blood cells from complement-mediated lysis.\r\n\r\nFlow cytometry in PNH patients reveals a **CD55- and CD59- cell** population, which represents the PNH clone. The cells lacking these surface markers (CD55 and CD59) are susceptible to complement-mediated lysis, leading to the characteristic hemolysis seen in PNH.\r\n\r\nA **CD55+ and CD59+** cell population is also observed, which represents the normal cells. These cells have intact CD55 and CD59 and are protected from complement-mediated lysis.\r\n\r\nThe **coexistence** of these **two populations** – one with and one without these markers – is diagnostic of PNH.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 643.","responses":[{"text":"Single type of cell population showing CD55+, CD59-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two types of cell populations: one CD55-, CD59- and second CD55+, CD59+","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Single type of cell population showing CD55+, CD59+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single type of cell population showing CD55-, CD59+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single type of cell population showing CD55-, CD59-","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10307,"text":"A dead body is brought to the mortuary for post mortem examination. The post-mortem rigidity is present throughout the body from head to toe. What is the estimated time of death?","explanation":"**Rigor mortis** is the temporary stiffening of muscles occurring after death. It begins within 2-6 hours after death, starting typically in the smaller muscles of the face and neck. It then progresses to involve the **entire body**, usually reaching its maximum extent at around **12-24 hours after death**. After its peak, rigor mortis gradually dissipates, starting from the same muscles where it began, and the body returns to a state of flaccidity. This resolution typically begins at about 24-36 hours and may be complete by 48-60 hours after death.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 148.","responses":[{"text":"36-48 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2-4 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"12-24 hours","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"4-18 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"24-36 hours","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10324,"text":"Which of these is a common manifestation of antiphospholipid syndrome?","explanation":"**Antiphospholipid syndrome** (APS) is an autoimmune disorder characterized by the presence of antiphospholipid antibodies in the blood, which can lead to hypercoagulability and an increased risk of thrombotic events. One of the significant clinical features of APS is the occurrence of **recurrent pregnancy losses**, particularly in the second and third trimesters.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Mouth ulcers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Raynaud phenomenon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alopecia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent abortions","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10325,"text":"Which of these is a direct thrombin inhibitor?","explanation":"**Dabigatran** is an oral anticoagulant that **directly inhibits thrombin**, a key enzyme involved in the coagulation cascade. It is used for various indications, including the prevention and treatment of conditions such as deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), and atrial fibrillation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRivaroxaban is a direct factor Xa inhibitor, not a direct thrombin inhibitor.\r\n\r\nHeparin is an indirect anticoagulant that enhances the activity of antithrombin III, leading to the inhibition of both thrombin and factor Xa.\r\n\r\nAbciximab is a glycoprotein IIb/IIIa receptor inhibitor that prevents platelet aggregation, but it does not directly inhibit thrombin.\r\n\r\nAspirin is an antiplatelet agent that works by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes and the production of thromboxane, which plays a role in platelet aggregation. It does not directly inhibit thrombin.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 446.","responses":[{"text":"Abciximab","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rivoraxaban","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dabigatran","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10326,"text":"Which of these drugs binds to ADP receptors on platelets and thus inhibits platelet aggregation?","explanation":"**Clopidogrel*** is an antiplatelet medication that works by irreversibly inhibiting the P2Y12 subtype of **ADP receptor** on the platelet surface. This inhibition prevents ADP-mediated activation of the GPIIb/IIIa receptor complex, thereby **reducing platelet aggregation** and thrombus formation. Clopidogrel is often used to prevent cardiovascular events in patients with coronary artery disease, peripheral vascular disease, and cerebrovascular disease.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAspirin inhibits platelet aggregation by irreversibly inhibiting the enzyme cyclooxygenase (COX), which leads to a decrease in thromboxane A2, a promoter of platelet aggregation. It does not act on ADP receptors.\r\n\r\nAbciximab is a monoclonal antibody that inhibits platelet aggregation by binding to the glycoprotein IIb/IIIa receptor on the platelet surface, not the ADP receptor.\r\n\r\nCilostazol works by inhibiting phosphodiesterase III, leading to an increase in cyclic AMP within platelets and vasodilation, but it does not bind directly to ADP receptors.\r\n\r\nDabigatran is an anticoagulant that inhibits thrombin (factor IIa) and does not have a direct effect on platelet ADP receptors.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 447.","responses":[{"text":"Abciximab","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dabigatran","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cilostazol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clopidogrel","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10328,"text":"A 17-year-old boy presents to the office with complaints of weakness and shortness of breath. On examination, he appears to have jaundice and also has splenomegaly. He was treated for malaria one week ago. Which test can be done to determine the cause of anemia?","explanation":"Jaundice and splenomegaly suggest **hemolytic anemia**. The most appropriate test to determine the cause of his anemia is the **glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) test**.\r\n\r\nG6PD is an enzyme that protects red blood cells from oxidative damage. Its deficiency can lead to hemolytic anemia, particularly following certain triggers such as certain **antimalarial drugs**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHemoglobin electrophoresi is used to identify hemoglobinopathies such as sickle cell disease or thalassemia. While it can be useful in some cases of anemia, the clinical context here points more towards hemolytic anemia secondary to G6PD deficiency.\r\n\r\nKaryotyping is used to analyze chromosomes and helps diagnose genetic disorders.\r\n\r\nWhile jaundice suggests liver involvement, the other symptoms (especially recent malaria infection) point more toward hemolysis as the cause of anemia, which is not directly assessed by liver function tests.\r\n\r\nA complete blood count (CBC)is a fundamental test and should be done as it provides important information about the blood cells, including the degree of anemia. However, in the context of the given clinical scenario, it would not be as specific as a G6PD test for determining the cause of the anemia.","reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 634.\r\n  \r\n2) Beutler E, Duparc S, G6PD Deficiency Working Group. Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency and antimalarial drug development. The American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene. Published October 2007. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17978087/","responses":[{"text":"Karyotype","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver function tests","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin electrophoresis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10329,"text":"A 4-year-old boy has a form of microcytic, hypochromic anemia. His skull X-ray shows a crew-cut appearance. Which form of thalassemia is most likely in this patient?","explanation":"**Beta thalassemia major**, also known as Cooley anemia, is a severe form of beta thalassemia characterized by a significant reduction in the production of beta-globin chains. This leads to anemia, hepatosplenomegaly, and skeletal abnormalities such as the \"**crew-cut**\" appearance on **skull X-ray** due to marrow expansion.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHemoglobin H disease is a form of alpha thalassemia and typically presents with a milder clinical phenotype compared to beta thalassemia major. It is characterized by a deficiency of alpha-globin chains and may result in moderate hemolytic anemia, but it does not typically lead to the severe skeletal abnormalities seen in beta-thalassemia major.\r\n\r\nAlpha thalassemia minor involves a deficiency of one or two alpha-globin chains and usually results in mild or no symptoms.\r\n\r\nBeta thalassemia minor, also known as beta thalassemia trait, is characterized by a reduced production of beta-globin chains but typically results in mild or no anemia.\r\n\r\nAlpha thalassemia minima is a carrier state with minimal clinical significance, as it involves the deletion of only one alpha-globin gene from each chromosome. It does not typically result in microcytic, hypochromic anemia or significant clinical symptoms.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 428.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha thalassemia minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha thalassemia minima","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta thalassemia major","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin H disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta thalassemia minor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10330,"text":"What is the inheritance pattern of glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency?","explanation":"**G6PD deficiency** is an **X-linked recessive** genetic disorder. This means that the gene responsible for G6PD is located on the X chromosome. Males have one X and one Y chromosome (XY), while females have two X chromosomes (XX).\r\n\r\nMales who inherit one copy of the mutated gene (X-linked recessive allele) from their carrier mother will express the disorder because they have no second X chromosome with a normal copy of the gene to compensate.\r\n\r\nFemales typically do not express the disorder unless they inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each carrier parent (homozygous for the X-linked recessive allele). Carrier females with one mutated gene and one normal gene usually do not manifest the condition but can pass it on to their offspring.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 432.","responses":[{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multifactorial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked recessive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked dominant","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10331,"text":"A dead body is brought in for post mortem examination and according to an eye witness, the death occurred 6-8 hours ago. Which of these signs will confirm the witness's account?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 120.","responses":[{"text":"Fully developed but fixed lividity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigor mortis in the entire body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fully developed but not fixed lividity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blister development under the skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greenish discoloration of the right flank","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10333,"text":"Which of these terms best describes the characteristics/features of disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC)?","explanation":"**Disseminated intravascular coagulation** (DIC) is a complex and severe condition characterized by the widespread activation of coagulation, which results in the formation of blood clots throughout the small blood vessels in the body. This process consumes large amounts of clotting factors and platelets, leading to a paradoxical state where initial clotting is followed by excessive bleeding due to the depletion of clotting resources.\r\n\r\nIn DIC, the red blood cells are mechanically damaged as they pass through the small blood vessels filled with clots, leading to hemolysis and the production of schistocytes (fragmented RBCs), which is a hallmark of **microangiopathic hemolytic anemia** (MAHA).\r\n\r\nIn DIC, there is an initial hypercoagulable state due to **widespread clotting**, followed by a hypocoagulable state with an increased risk of **bleeding** due to the consumption of clotting factors and platelets.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 663-665.","responses":[{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) + uremia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) + coagulopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) + neurological symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10337,"text":"What is the shape of entry wounds formed as a result of stabbing?","explanation":"The shape of **entry wounds** formed as a result of stabbing is typically **elliptical**, particularly if the **stabbing** occurs perpendicularly to the skin surface. This is due to the way the sharp edges of the weapon, such as a knife, interact with the skin.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIf the stabbing occurs at an oblique angle, the wound may appear more linear or slit-like, although an elliptic wound is more common.\r\n\r\nCircular wounds are more typical of gunshot entry wounds, especially when the gun is fired from close range.\r\n\r\nWhile some stab wounds can have irregular margins, especially with serrated or irregular blades, the typical shape of a stab wound from a regular blade is more often elliptical.\r\n\r\nPuckered wounds are generally associated with gunshot wounds, where the skin is drawn inward due to the vacuum effect created by the bullet's path.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 226.","responses":[{"text":"Elliptical","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Circular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Linear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irregular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Puckered","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10343,"text":"During the examination of a dead body, greenish discoloration in the right iliac fossa is seen. The abdomen is distended and the limbs are rigid. What term best describes the condition?","explanation":"Greenish discoloration in the right iliac fossa is a sign of **putrefaction**, which is associated with **gas stiffening**. Bacterial activity in the body produces gases such as methane and hydrogen sulfide. These gases accumulate in the tissues and body cavities, leading to distention of the abdomen and causing muscle rigidity.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRigor mortis is the stiffening of muscles that occurs shortly after death due to the depletion of ATP in muscle fibers. It typically begins within a few hours after death and gradually resolves over the next 24-48 hours.\r\n\r\nCold stiffening occurs when a body stiffens up due to cold temperatures.\r\n\r\nLike cold stiffening, heat can affect the rate at which rigor mortis sets in, but it is not the term used to describe the stiffening process itself.\r\n\r\nCadaveric spasm is a rare form of muscle stiffening that occurs at the moment of death and is typically associated with deaths involving extreme physical or emotional stress.","reference":"1) Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 150.\r\n2) Shedge R, Krishan K, Warrier V, Kanchan T. Postmortem changes. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539741/","responses":[{"text":"Heat stiffening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigor mortis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cadaveric spasm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cold stiffening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gas stiffening","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10344,"text":"Which of these methods of tattoo removal does not leave a scar?","explanation":"**Laser tattoo removal** is a popular method due to its effectiveness and **lower risk of scarring** compared to other methods. It works by using laser light to break down the tattoo pigment into smaller particles, which are then removed by the body's immune system. Multiple sessions are usually required, depending on the size, location, and color of the tattoo.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nElectrolysis involves the use of electrical current to remove tattoos, which can be quite invasive and has a higher risk of scarring.\r\n\r\nCarbon dioxide snow (cryotherapy), uses extreme cold to destroy tattooed skin cells. It carries a risk of scarring due to potential tissue damage from the cold.\r\n\r\nThe application of caustic substances to remove tattoos is highly discouraged due to its destructive nature to the skin, which almost invariably leads to scarring.\r\n\r\nDermabrasion involves the mechanical sanding down of the skin's upper layers where the tattoo ink resides. It is quite abrasive and has a high likelihood of leaving scars.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 71.","responses":[{"text":"Electrolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon dioxide snow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dermabrasion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caustic substances","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Laser beam","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10346,"text":"A 2-year-old boy presents with frontal and parietal bossing and a history of severe pallor for 1 month. His mother and father are first cousins. He has another sibling who has had blood transfusions. Hemoglobin electrophoresis shows an HbA1 of 15 percent and HbF of 85 percent. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Beta thalassemia major**, also known as Cooley anemia, is a severe form of thalassemia that becomes apparent in the first two years of life. It is characterized by a marked reduction or absence of beta-globin chain synthesis, leading to severe anemia.\r\n\r\n**Frontal and parietal bossing** is a typical craniofacial deformity seen in beta-thalassemia major, resulting from bone marrow expansion due to ineffective erythropoiesis while severe **pallor** indicates severe anemia, which is a hallmark of beta-thalassemia major. In this condition, the body compensates for the reduced beta-globin chain synthesis by producing more gamma chains, leading to the formation of very small amounts of HbA1 and **high** amounts of **HbF**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHemoglobin Barts is seen in alpha thalassemia major (hydrops fetalis), a condition incompatible with life beyond the fetal period.\r\n\r\nHemoglobin H disease is a form of alpha-thalassemia, not beta-thalassemia. It is less severe than beta thalassemia major.\r\n\r\nWhile sickle cell disease can present with severe anemia, the hemoglobin electrophoresis typically shows a predominance of HbS, not HbF as in this case.\r\n\r\nBeta thalassemia minor is the carrier or mild form of beta thalassemia, which generally presents with mild anemia and does not typically result in the severe clinical picture seen in this patient.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 428.","responses":[{"text":"Hemoglobin Barts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta thalassemia major","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta thalassemia minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin H disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10349,"text":"What is the screening test of choice for deep venous thromboembolism?","explanation":"**D-dimer** is a blood test that measures the presence of a substance released when a blood clot breaks up. It is often used as an **initial screening test** to assess the likelihood of **deep venous thromboembolism** (DVT) or pulmonary embolism (PE). Elevated levels of D-dimer can suggest the presence of abnormal blood clotting, but it is not specific to DVT.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDoppler ultrasound is a common imaging method used to visualize blood flow in the deep veins of the legs and is considered a definitive diagnostic tool for DVT rather than a screening tool.\r\n\r\nCT scan, CT angiography, and MRI are also used in the evaluation of DVT and PE but are typically reserved for cases where D-dimer results are inconclusive or when there is a need for more detailed anatomical information.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 187.","responses":[{"text":"Doppler ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"D-dimer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography (CT) scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computed tomography (CT) angiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10352,"text":"Which of these terms best describes thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura?","explanation":"**Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura** (TTP) is a rare blood disorder characterized by the formation of small blood clots (thrombi) in the small blood vessels throughout the body. This leads to a distinctive triad of microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) neurologic symptoms, and thrombocytopenia.\r\n\r\nHemolysis occurs due to physical damage as the cells pass through the narrowed, clot-filled small vessels.\r\n\r\nNeurologic symptoms can vary widely but often include headaches, confusion, seizures, and in severe cases, stroke-like symptoms. They are caused by reduced blood flow to the brain due to the small vessel thrombi.\r\n\r\nThere is also a reduction in platelet count because platelets are consumed in the formation of numerous small clots throughout the body's circulation.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) plus neurologic symptoms and thrombocytopenia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macroangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) plus coagulopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA) plus thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10354,"text":"A 12-year-old girl is sent for age determination. On which part of the body will the X-ray be performed?","explanation":"A **hand and wrist X-ray** is commonly used for assessing skeletal maturity and estimating a person's biological **age**, especially in pediatric cases. The growth plates (epiphyseal plates) in the bones of the hand and wrist have well-defined patterns of development and closure during childhood and adolescence. Radiologists and physicians can examine these patterns to estimate a person's age with reasonable accuracy.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nX-rays of the shoulder and pelvis are used to determine the age of adults.\r\n\r\nX-rays of the skull and sternum are typically preferred for the age determination of the elderly.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 62.","responses":[{"text":"Pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skull","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hand and wrist","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shoulder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10356,"text":"What is the correct definition of anemia?","explanation":"**Anemia** is a condition characterized by a decrease in the number of red blood cells or a decrease in the amount of hemoglobin in the blood, which leads to a reduced oxygen-carrying capacity. It is primarily characterized by a decrease in the circulating red blood cell mass, resulting in symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, paleness, and shortness of breath.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDecreased platelet count is a characteristic of thrombocytopenia, a condition involving a low platelet count.\r\n\r\nDecreased total blood volume is not specific to anemia and can occur in various conditions, including hemorrhage or dehydration.\r\n\r\nDecreased WBC count is characteristic of leukopenia, a condition involving a low white blood cell count.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 629.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased total blood volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased WBC count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased total red blood cell mass","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased platelet count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased circulating red blood cell mass","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10357,"text":"What is the mode of action of warfarin?","explanation":"**Warfarin** is an anticoagulant medication that works by inhibiting the enzyme **vitamin K epoxide reductase** (VKORC1), specifically VKORC1 in the liver. This enzyme plays a crucial role in the synthesis of biologically active forms of vitamin K, which are necessary for the production of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X in the coagulation cascade.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nInhibition of factor Xa is the mode of action of direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) like apixaban and rivaroxaban.\r\n\r\nInhibition of cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes is the mode of action of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like aspirin.\r\n\r\nInhibition of ADP receptors is the mode of action of antiplatelet medications like clopidogrel, which inhibits ADP receptors on platelets, thereby reducing platelet aggregation.\r\n\r\nDirect thrombin inhibitors interfere with the activity of thrombin in the coagulation cascade.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 446.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibition of ADP receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of factor Xa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of vitamin K epoxide reductase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of COX enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10361,"text":"Which medication can commonly lead to a hypercoagulable state?","explanation":"**Oral contraceptive pills** contain hormones, such as estrogen and progestin, which can increase the risk of blood clot formation in some individuals. This can lead to a **hypercoagulable state**, making individuals more prone to developing deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), or other clotting disorders.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAspirin is an antiplatelet agent that reduces the risk of blood clot formation and is often used to prevent clot-related conditions.\r\n\r\nWarfarin is an anticoagulant that inhibits blood clotting and is used to treat or prevent blood clots.\r\n\r\nAntibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are not known to cause a hypercoagulable state.\r\n\r\nDiphenhydramine is an antihistamine commonly used to relieve allergy symptoms and does not have a significant effect on blood clotting.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 681.","responses":[{"text":"Diphenydramine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral contraceptive pill","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10362,"text":"Which type of anemia is associated with Plummer-Vinson syndrome?","explanation":"**Plummer-Vinson syndrome**, also known as Paterson-Kelly syndrome, is characterized by a triad of symptoms - iron deficiency anemia, dysphagia, and glossitis. The anemia is typically due to chronic **iron deficiency**, often resulting from poor iron absorption related to chronic gastrointestinal issues.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 387.","responses":[{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10365,"text":"A 24-year-old male presents to the office with an enlarging lump on his neck. Lymph node biopsy reveals lymphocytic infiltration in the germinal center along with tingible body macrophages in a 'starry sky' appearance. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The '**starry sky**' appearance is a characteristic histological pattern seen in **Burkitt lymphoma**. It is caused by the high proliferation rate of the lymphoma cells and the phagocytosis of cell debris by tingible body macrophages.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHodgkin lymphoma has distinct Reed-Sternberg cells that are not seen in Burkitt lymphoma.\r\n\r\nFollicular lymphoma typically presents with follicular architecture and lacks the 'starry sky' appearance.\r\n\r\nAcute lymphoblastic leukemia is a leukemia characterized by the presence of immature lymphoblasts in the bone marrow.\r\n\r\nDiffuse large B cell lymphoma may present with various histological patterns but does not typically have the characteristic 'starry sky' appearance.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 439.","responses":[{"text":"Diffuse large B cell lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute lymphoblastic leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hodgkin lymphoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burkitt lymphoma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10367,"text":"A 15-year-old child presents with low-grade fever and a mass on the right side of the neck which has been enlarging for the past two weeks. The mass is an enlarged lymph node in the anterior cervical chain. It is firm, non-tender, and rubbery. Which test needs to be ordered to confirm the diagnosis?","explanation":"A lymph node **biopsy** is typically the most definitive and commonly used diagnostic test in cases of **enlarged lymph nodes** when there is uncertainty about the cause. In this case, the presence of a firm, non-tender, rubbery lymph node that has been growing in size raises concerns about potential underlying causes, including infectious, inflammatory, and neoplastic conditions.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile a CT scan can provide detailed imaging of the neck and lymph nodes, it is not typically the first-line diagnostic test for evaluating an enlarged lymph node, especially in a pediatric patient. It may be considered as a follow-up study or for further characterization if needed, but it does not confirm the specific cause of lymphadenopathy.\r\n\r\nBone marrow evaluation is not typically the initial test performed to evaluate an enlarged lymph node in the neck. This procedure is usually reserved for cases where there is suspicion of hematologic malignancies or systemic involvement. It is not the primary diagnostic test for localized lymphadenopathy.\r\n\r\nPositron emission tomography (PET) scans are used to detect areas of increased metabolic activity in the body, which can help evaluate the extent of disease in certain malignancies. However, a PET scan is not typically the initial diagnostic test for evaluating an isolated enlarged lymph node.\r\n\r\nWhile an ultrasound of the neck can provide detailed imaging of the lymph nodes and help characterize their size, shape, and internal characteristics, it is still an imaging study and does not provide a definitive diagnosis.","reference":"Mohseni S, Shojaiefard A, Khorgami Z, Alinejad S, Ghorbani A, Ghafouri A. Peripheral lymphadenopathy: approach and diagnostic tools. Iran J Med Sci. 2014;39(2 Suppl):158-170. Accessed April 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3993046/","responses":[{"text":"Ultrasound neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph node biopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow aspiration and trephine biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PET scan","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11532,"text":"Which stage of erythropoiesis has a condensed nucleus with 34% hemoglobin and no endoplasmic reticulum?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Reticulocyte","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polychromatic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orthochromatic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11533,"text":"A child presented with the complaint of right armpit pain in the outpatient department of a hospital. On examination, the doctor noticed an abrasion on his forearm. A biopsy was suggested which revealed stellate necrotizing granuloma. Which of the following could be responsible for that?","explanation":"**Stellate necrotizing granuloma** is a characteristic histopathological finding associated with cat-scratch disease, which is caused by ***Bartonella henselae***, a bacterium commonly transmitted through cat scratches or bites. It often presents with lymphadenopathy and can lead to skin lesions and regional lymph node involvement, which could explain the right armpit pain in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 428.","responses":[{"text":"Epstein-Barr virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytomegalovirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yersinia pestis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bartonella","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11534,"text":"According to WHO classification, how many categories is myelodysplastic syndrome divided into?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 621. \r\n\r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 961.","responses":[{"text":"7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"8","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11588,"text":"What is the maximum amount of hemoglobin that can be concentrated in the red blood cell fluid?","explanation":"Hemoglobin is the protein inside RBCs responsible for carrying oxygen from the lungs to the body's tissues and organs.  In a normal, healthy red blood cell (RBC), the **maximum** concentration of **hemoglobin** is around **37 g/dL**. The high concentration of hemoglobin in RBCs allows them to efficiently transport oxygen.","reference":"Hall, John E. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed., Elsevier, 2016: 445.","responses":[{"text":"37 g/dL","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"15 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"19 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"25 g/dL","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11589,"text":"What is the mean age of occurrence of myelodysplastic syndrome?","explanation":"While **myelodysplastic syndrome** (MDS) can affect people of various age groups, it is more prevalent among the elderly population. It is most commonly diagnosed in older adults, with a significant portion of cases occurring in individuals who are **70 years** of age or older.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 615.","responses":[{"text":"40","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"60","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"80","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"50","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"70","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11590,"text":"Which transfusion product of blood carries the highest risk of bacterial contamination?","explanation":"**Platelets** are stored at room temperature (20-24°C) to maintain their functionality. This storage condition makes platelet transfusion products more susceptible to **bacterial growth** compared to other blood components, which are typically stored at cooler temperatures.\r\n\r\nThe warm environment in which platelets are stored can allow bacteria to multiply more rapidly if contamination occurs. For this reason, platelet transfusions are associated with a higher risk of bacterial contamination than packed red blood cells, fresh frozen plasma, whole blood, or cryoprecipitate.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 930, 933.","responses":[{"text":"Whole blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fresh frozen plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryoprecipitate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Packed red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelets","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11591,"text":"Which of the following white blood cells produce the major basic protein?","explanation":"**Eosinophils** are a type of white blood cell known for their involvement in allergic reactions and parasitic infections. They contain granules that contain various proteins, including the **major basic protein** (MBP).\r\n\r\nThe major basic protein plays a role in the defense against parasitic infections and is involved in the immune response. It can also contribute to tissue damage in certain allergic conditions, such as asthma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMegakaryocytes are responsible for producing platelets.\r\n\r\nBasophils contain granules with substances like histamine and heparin but do not produce the major basic protein.\r\n\r\nMonocytes are a type of white blood cell that can differentiate into macrophages.\r\n\r\nNeutrophils primarily produce enzymes and antimicrobial proteins to combat bacterial infections.","reference":"Hall, John E. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed., Elsevier, 2016: 462.","responses":[{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megakaryocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11592,"text":"A 55-year-old male has severe lumbar vertebral pain. His complete blood count shows normocytic normochromic anemia with a markedly raised erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR). The clinical diagnosis by the physician is multiple myeloma. Assuming that the clinical diagnosis is correct, what will be the most characteristic finding on the peripheral film of his peripheral smear?","explanation":"**Multiple myeloma** is a type of blood cancer that affects plasma cells. One of the hallmark features in the laboratory findings of multiple myeloma is the presence of a high serum protein concentration, particularly due to monoclonal immunoglobulin (usually IgG or IgA). This high protein concentration, especially the elevated immunoglobulins, can lead to **altered erythrocyte sedimentation** and the characteristic appearance of red blood cells (RBCs) stacking up like coins, known as **rouleaux formation**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMacro-ovalocytes are typically seen in megaloblastic anemias, which are due to vitamin B12 or folate deficiency.\r\n\r\nTarget cells are often associated with liver disease and hemoglobinopathies like thalassemia or sickle cell anemia.\r\n\r\nFragmented RBCs can be seen in conditions like disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), mechanical hemolysis, or thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP).\r\n\r\nAlthough tear drop cells can be seen in a variety of conditions, including myelofibrosis and other myeloproliferative disorders, they are not a characteristic finding in multiple myeloma.","reference":"Sattar, Husain A. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com, 2019: 57.","responses":[{"text":"Tear drop cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fragmented RBCs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rouleaux formation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Macro-ovalocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Target cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11593,"text":"Which of the following factors is required for red blood cell maturation?","explanation":"**Vitamin B12**, also known as cobalamin, is necessary for DNA synthesis within the bone marrow, which is a critical step in the **maturation** and division of **erythroid precursors** in red blood cell production.\r\n\r\nA deficiency in vitamin B12 can lead to megaloblastic anemia, where RBC precursors (megaloblasts) fail to mature properly, resulting in large, immature red blood cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile iron is essential for hemoglobin synthesis within red blood cells, it is not directly involved in the maturation process of the cells themselves. Iron deficiency affects hemoglobin content, leading to microcytic anemia.\r\n\r\nAlthough vitamin C plays a role in iron absorption and general cellular function, it is not directly involved in the maturation of red blood cells.\r\n\r\nThiamine (vitamin B1) is not specifically required for RBC maturation.","reference":"Hall, John E. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed., Elsevier, 2016: 449.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11597,"text":"Which of the following chromosomal abnormality is not observed in myelodysplastic syndrome?","explanation":"Myelodysplastic syndromes (MDS) are a group of heterogeneous bone marrow disorders characterized by dysplasia in one or more of the major myeloid cell lines and an increased risk of progression to acute myeloid leukemia (AML).  Deletion of 18q is not commonly associated with myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS). \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe deletion of the long arm of chromosome 5 (5q) is particularly associated with a subtype of MDS known as 5q- syndrome.\r\n\r\nMDS patients often present with a complex karyotype, which involves multiple chromosomal abnormalities.\r\n\r\nThe presence of an extra chromosome 8 is often found in MDS patients.\r\n\r\nLoss of chromosome 7 or deletion of its long arm (7q) is a well-recognized abnormality in MDS.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Deletion of 18q","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trisomy 8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complex karyotype","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monosomy 5/ deletion of 5q","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monosomy 7/ deletion of 7q","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11599,"text":"Which of the following chromosomal abnormalities is absent in chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) or small lymphocytic lymphoma (SLL)?","explanation":"Translocation involving chromosomes 14 and 18 is not typically seen in CLL or SLL. This type of translocation is more commonly associated with other types of B-cell lymphomas, such as follicular lymphoma.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nDeletion of the long arm of chromosome 11 (11q-) is another common genetic abnormality in CLL and SLL.\r\n\r\nDeletion of 13q is a common genetic abnormality in CLL and SLL, seen in a significant proportion of cases. It is often associated with a favorable prognosis.\r\n\r\nDeletion of the short arm of chromosome 17 (17p-) is also seen in CLL and SLL and is associated with a poorer prognosis due to the loss of the tumor suppressor gene TP53.\r\n\r\nTrisomy 12 i.e., the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 12 is seen in a subset of CLL and SLL cases.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 434.","responses":[{"text":"Translocation 14:18","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deletion of 13q","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deletion of 11q","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deletion of 17p","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trisomy 12q","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11600,"text":"The age of a young boy needs to be determined. Dental X-ray reveals mixed dentition and an examination of the oral cavity reveals that the first and second molars have erupted. What is the approximate age of this boy?","explanation":"In dental development, the age of a child can be estimated by examining the eruption pattern of teeth. During the **mixed dentition** phase, a child has both primary (deciduous) and permanent teeth. This phase typically begins around the age of 6 and lasts until about **12-13 years**.\r\n\r\nGiven that both the **first** and **second permanent molars** have erupted, and the child is still in the mixed dentition phase, the most accurate estimate of the boy's age would be 12 to 13 years.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\n6 to 7 years of age corresponds with the eruption of the first permanent molars, but it is too early for the second permanent molars.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 69.","responses":[{"text":"10 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"8 to 9 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"12 to 13 years","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"6 to 7 years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 to 12 years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11602,"text":"The age of a male needs to be determined. Dental X-ray reveals mixed dentition and an examination of the oral cavity reveals that his wisdom tooth has erupted. What is the approximate age of this person?","explanation":"In most individuals, **wisdom teeth**, also known as third molars, typically erupt between the ages of **17** and 25. The term \"**mixed dentition**\" refers to a phase in dental development when a person has both their primary (baby) teeth and permanent teeth. When the wisdom teeth have erupted, it usually indicates that the individual is in late adolescence or early adulthood.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Hematology module, Forensic slides, Topic: Age determination by teeth.","responses":[{"text":"18+ years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"15+ years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20+ years","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"17+ years","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"25+ years","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11613,"text":"A child has had a fever for 15 days. He has been taking antipyretics and antibiotics. His complete blood count report shows leukopenia and absolute neutropenia. What would be the cause of neutropenia?","explanation":"Some drugs can suppress the bone marrow's ability to produce neutrophils, leading to neutropenia **drug-induced neutropenia**. This condition can occur as a side effect of certain medications, including **antibiotics**. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nCongenital neutropenia is a rare genetic condition where individuals are born with a decreased number of neutrophils. While it's a possibility, it's less likely in a child who has been previously well and developed symptoms after taking antibiotics.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 deficiency can cause various blood abnormalities, including anemia, but it is not typically associated with neutropenia.\r\n\r\nNeutropenia is a component of aplastic anemia, but it would typically be associated with other abnormalities in the CBC as well, such as anemia and thrombocytopenia.\r\n\r\nChemotherapy can lead to neutropenia as a side effect, but this would typically occur in individuals who are receiving chemotherapy for cancer treatment.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 582.","responses":[{"text":"Congenital neutropenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug-induced neutropenia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deficiency of vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemotherapy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11614,"text":"Which of the following is the cause of Henoch-Schonlein purpura?","explanation":"**Henoch-Schönlein purpura** (HSP) is a medical condition characterized by inflammation of small blood vessels, primarily involving the skin, joints, gastrointestinal tract, and kidneys. The primary cause of HSP is **vasculitis**, which is the inflammation of blood vessels. This inflammation can result in a range of symptoms, including the characteristic purpura, joint pain, abdominal pain, and kidney involvement.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile anemia may occur as a result of chronic inflammation in some cases, it is not the underlying cause of HSP.\r\n\r\nThrombocytopenia is a condition characterized by a low platelet count in the blood. While bleeding and petechiae (small red or purple dots on the skin) can occur in thrombocytopenia, it is not the cause of HSP. HSP is primarily a vasculitic disorder.\r\n\r\nPolycythemia is a condition characterized by an elevated number of red blood cells in the blood.\r\n\r\nHemophilia A is a genetic bleeding disorder caused by a deficiency of clotting factor VIII.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 657.","responses":[{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasculitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11615,"text":"What is the composition of hemoglobin A2 (HbA2)?","explanation":"Hemoglobin A2 (HbA2) is a specific type of hemoglobin found in adult humans. It is composed of two alpha (α) globin chains and two delta (δ) globin chains.\r\n\r\nHbA is the most common adult hemoglobin and consists of two alpha (α) and two beta (β) globin chains.\r\n\r\nAlpha (α) and gamma (γ) globin chains are associated with fetal hemoglobin (HbF).","reference":"Le, Tao, and Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 412.","responses":[{"text":"α2, δ2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"γ2, ε2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α2, γ2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β2, γ2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α2, β2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11641,"text":"Which one of the following is not one of the reasons why oral iron gluconate is not preferred?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Karen Whalen, et al. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed., Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins, 2019: 566.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2) Nguyen, Minhthao, and Prasanna Tadi. “Iron Supplementation.” StatPearls, StatPearls Publishing, 2022. PubMed, http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557376/","responses":[{"text":"Vomiting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upset GIT","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metallic taste","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Black stools","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11642,"text":"A 32-year-old woman has given birth to a stillborn hydropic baby with hepatosplenomegaly. What will be seen in her hemoglobin electrophoresis?","explanation":"**Hemoglobin Barts (Hb Barts)** is typically associated with alpha-thalassemia, a genetic disorder characterized by a deficiency in the production of alpha-globin chains of hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nIn cases of severe alpha-thalassemia, such as Hb Barts **hydrops fetalis** syndrome, the affected fetus is unable to produce functional hemoglobin and, as a result, experiences severe anemia and severe generalized edema in utero. This condition is incompatible with life, leading to **stillbirth** or neonatal death shortly after birth.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 642.","responses":[{"text":"HbS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HbA2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hb Barts","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HbF","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11643,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of dipyridamole?","explanation":"**Dipyridamole** works by inhibiting the enzyme phosphodiesterase, which normally breaks down cAMP. By **inhibiting phosphodiesterase**, dipyridamole increases the levels of cAMP within platelets and vascular smooth muscle cells. **Elevated cAMP** levels lead to various effects, including inhibition of platelet aggregation and vasodilation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIrreversible inhibition of the binding of adenosine diphosphate (ADP) to its receptors is the mechanism of action of P2Y12 receptor inhibitors.\r\n\r\nInhibition of the activation of glycoprotein (GP) receptor IIb/IIIa receptors is associated with drugs like abciximab and eptifibatide, which are glycoprotein IIb/IIIa receptor antagonists.\r\n\r\nIntegrin antagonists act by interacting with the arginine glycine aspartic acid sequence of fibrinogen.","reference":"Le, Tao, and Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Irreversibly inhibiting binding of adenosine diphosphate (ADP) to its receptors on platelets","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocking the binding of fibrinogen to von Willebrand factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibiting the activation of glycoprotein (GP) receptor llb/llla receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interacting with arginine glycine aspartic acid sequence of fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increasing cAMP by inhibiting nucleotide phosphodiesterase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11644,"text":"How does the bleeding diathesis due to vascular disorder appear?","explanation":"**Petechiae** are small, pinpoint red or purple spots on the skin that result from tiny hemorrhages or bleeding under the skin's surface. They are a characteristic feature of bleeding disorders that affect the blood vessels, such as vasculitis or disorders of blood vessel integrity.\r\n\r\n**Purpura**, on the other hand, are larger areas of bleeding under the skin, appearing as purple or red patches. They are also indicative of vascular disorders that lead to increased fragility or permeability of blood vessels.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSoft tissue changes are not a primary characteristic of vascular disorders causing bleeding diathesis.\r\n\r\nJoint deformity is more commonly associated with musculoskeletal disorders or inflammatory joint conditions, not vascular disorders.\r\n\r\nTachycardia refers to a rapid heart rate and is generally not a direct symptom of a bleeding diathesis due to a vascular disorder.\r\n\r\nHematomas are localized collections of blood outside blood vessels and are more likely to be associated with trauma.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 450, 452.","responses":[{"text":"Joint deformity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Soft issue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Petechiae and purpura","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11669,"text":"Which of the following is the most common type of mutation seen in β thalassemia?","explanation":"**β-thalassemia** is most frequently caused by **mutations** affecting RNA **splicing**. These mutations occur in the intronic or exonic regions of the β-globin gene and disrupt the normal splicing process during mRNA processing. This leads to abnormal or reduced production of the β-globin chain.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile chromosomal translocations can cause various genetic disorders, they are not a common cause of β-thalassemia.\r\n\r\nDeletions in the β-globin gene can occur, but they are more characteristic of α-thalassemia.\r\n\r\nChain terminator mutations introduce a premature stop codon, leading to the early termination of protein synthesis.\r\n\r\nMutations in the promoter region of the β-globin gene can reduce gene expression. However, these are less common compared to splicing mutations in causing β-thalassemia.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 638-639.","responses":[{"text":"Splicing mutation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chain terminator mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Translocation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gene deletion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Promoter region mutation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11670,"text":"A body is recovered from a densely populated neighborhood. The body is in an advanced stage of putrefaction, with greenish discoloration of the skin, distention of the abdomen, and muscle rigidity. Which of the following is the cause of rigidity in this case?","explanation":"**Gas stiffening** occurs during the advanced stages of putrefaction when bacterial activity in the body produces gases such as methane and hydrogen sulfide. These gases accumulate in the tissues and body cavities, leading to distention of the abdomen and causing muscle rigidity. The greenish discoloration of the skin is also a characteristic feature of **advanced putrefaction**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nRigor mortis is the stiffening of muscles that occurs shortly after death due to the depletion of ATP in muscle fibers. It typically begins within a few hours after death and gradually resolves over the next 24-48 hours.\r\n\r\nInstantaneous rigor is a theoretical concept and does not occur in actual human physiology.\r\n\r\nCold stiffening is a process that occurs in some animals after death when they are exposed to cold temperatures.\r\n\r\nHigh temperatures can accelerate the process of putrefaction, but they do not cause muscle rigidity in the same way as gas stiffening.","reference":"(1) Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 150.\r\n\r\n(2) Shedge R, Krishan K, Warrier V, Kanchan T. Postmortem changes. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 5, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539741/","responses":[{"text":"Instantaneous rigor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rigor mortis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gas stiffening","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heat stiffening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cold stiffening","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11671,"text":"Due to which of the following preformed antibodies is the reaction caused in acute hemolytic reaction?","explanation":"In **acute hemolytic reactions**, such as ABO blood group incompatibility or transfusion reactions, **IgM antibodies** are often responsible. IgM antibodies are large pentameric molecules that are efficient at agglutinating and lysing red blood cells. These antibodies can activate the complement system, leading to rapid and extensive destruction of the incompatible red blood cells.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed., Elsevier Saunders, 2015: 665.","responses":[{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11682,"text":"Which of the following conditions is known to cause ineffective intramedullary hematopoiesis and pancytopenia?","explanation":"**Aplastic anemia** is a disorder characterized by a reduction in the number of blood cells (pancytopenia) due to a decrease in the production of these cells within the bone marrow. This decrease in hematopoiesis within the bone marrow is referred to as ineffective intramedullary hematopoiesis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHypersplenism refers to the overactivity of the spleen, which can result in the destruction of blood cells, particularly red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. However, it leads to increased extramedullary hematopoiesis to compensate for the loss of blood cells.\r\n\r\nMyelodysplastic syndrome (MDS) is a group of disorders characterized by abnormal and dysplastic (malformed) blood cell production in the bone marrow. While MDS can lead to cytopenias (low blood cell counts), it does not necessarily affect all cell lines.\r\n\r\nRenal failure primarily affects the kidneys and can lead to anemia due to decreased production of erythropoietin, but it does not directly cause pancytopenia or ineffective intramedullary hematopoiesis.\r\n\r\nAnemia of chronic disease is associated with chronic illnesses and is characterized by reduced red blood cell production.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 653.","responses":[{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myelodysplastic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersplenism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11684,"text":"A child is brought to the clinic by his parents with a complaint of fatigue. His parents further inform about their family history of blood disorder. His laboratory results show hemoglobin 9.6 mg/dL, reticulocytes 7%, and mean corpuscular volume (MCV) 87 fl. His blood smear shows the presence of spherocytes. What is the possible diagnosis?","explanation":"**Spherocytes** are abnormally shaped red blood cells with a spherical appearance. Their presence suggests a structural problem with the red blood cells, which is characteristic of hereditary spherocytosis.\r\n\r\n**Hereditary spherocytosis** is a genetic disorder known to run in families, often with a history of blood disorders among relatives. A hemoglobin level of 9.6 mg/dL indicates **anemia**, which results from the reduced lifespan of abnormal red blood cells. The **reticulocyte count** is **elevated**, suggesting that the bone marrow is trying to compensate for the anemia by producing more red blood cells.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nG6PD deficiency is typically associated with episodes of hemolysis triggered by certain medications or infections. It does not lead to the presence of spherocytes on a blood smear or a family history of blood disorders.\r\n\r\nSickle cell disease, while causing anemia, is characterized by sickle-shaped red blood cells, not spherocytes.\r\n\r\nMyeloproliferative disorder involves the overproduction of myeloid cells, which can result in increased red blood cell counts.\r\n\r\nAplastic anemia is characterized by a reduction in all blood cell types, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 632-633.","responses":[{"text":"G6PD deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hereditary spherocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myeloproliferative disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11685,"text":"Owl-like appearance is found in which cells present in Hodgkin lymphoma?","explanation":"**Reed-Sternberg cells** are large, abnormal, multinucleated cells that are characteristic of Hodgkin's lymphoma when observed under a microscope. These cells are often described as having an \"**owl-like**\" appearance because of their binucleated or multinucleated structure with prominent nucleoli, which can resemble the eyes of an owl. This distinctive appearance is a key diagnostic feature of **Hodgkin lymphoma**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSpur cells, also known as acanthocytes, are a type of red blood cell that is misshapen and has spiky or irregular projections on its surface. They are typically associated with conditions like abetalipoproteinemia and neuroacanthocytosis syndromes.\r\n\r\nBite cells are red blood cells with characteristic \"bitten\" or notched edges seen in individuals with glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency. These cells result from the removal of Heinz bodies (denatured hemoglobin) within the red blood cell. Bite cells are a sign of G6PD deficiency.\r\n\r\nTeardrop cells, also known as dacrocytes, are abnormally shaped red blood cells that appear elongated and often have a teardrop or pear-like appearance. They can be seen in various hematological disorders, including myelofibrosis.\r\n\r\nHeinz bodies are inclusions of denatured hemoglobin within red blood cells. They are associated with conditions such as G6PD deficiency and various forms of hemolytic anemia.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Teardrop cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reed-Sternberg cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heinz bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bite cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spur cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11689,"text":"Which of the following drugs is given in chronic granulomatous disease?","explanation":"**Chronic granulomatous disease** (CGD) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by defects in the function of phagocytes, particularly neutrophils and macrophages. Patients with CGD are prone to recurrent and severe bacterial and fungal infections due to their impaired ability to kill certain types of bacteria and fungi.\r\n\r\n**Interferon gamma** (IFN-γ) is a medication used in the treatment of(CGD). It is a cytokine that can stimulate the immune system and improve the phagocytes' ability to combat infections.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTrastuzumab is a targeted therapy used in certain types of cancer.\r\n\r\nInterferon alpha and interferon beta are used in the treatment of various viral infections and autoimmune conditions.\r\n\r\nTelbivudine is an antiviral medication used to treat hepatitis B.","reference":"Errante PR, Frazão JB, Condino-Neto A. The use of interferon-gamma therapy in chronic granulomatous disease. Recent Patents on Anti-Infective Drug Discovery. Published November 2008. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18991804/","responses":[{"text":"Interferon gamma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interferon beta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Telbivudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interferon alpha","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trastuzumab","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11690,"text":"In beta-thalassemia major, which of the following is observed?","explanation":"**Beta-thalassemia major** is a genetic disorder characterized by a deficiency or absence of beta-globin chains in hemoglobin. This results in an imbalance between the alpha and non-alpha globin chains. Due to the imbalance, there is excess production of **alpha globin chains**. These excess alpha chains tend to precipitate and form insoluble aggregates within the red blood cells. This process is known as intracellular hemoglobin precipitation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 414.","responses":[{"text":"Precipitation of delta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Precipitation of gamma chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Precipitation of zeta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Precipitation of beta chains","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Precipitation of alpha chains","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11691,"text":"A 50-year-old man has large-sized red blood cells and hemoglobin is also below normal. Which of the following will he be prescribed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hariz A, Bhattacharya PT. Megaloblastic anemia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 9, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537254/","responses":[{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin  C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11692,"text":"Deficiency of which of the following comes with damage to myelin sheath?","explanation":"**Vitamin B12** plays a crucial role in the synthesis of DNA and RNA in the nervous system, and its **deficiency** can result in **demyelination**, which is the breakdown of the myelin sheath. This condition can lead to neurological problems, including numbness, tingling, weakness, and difficulty with balance and coordination.","reference":"Le, Tao, and Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2022: 428.","responses":[{"text":"Folic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11693,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect about aspirin?","explanation":"**Aspirin** is commonly used as an antiplatelet agent for prophylactic purposes, such as preventing cardiovascular events like heart attacks and strokes. **Low dose** aspirin is the standard dose used for **prophylaxis** because it effectively inhibits platelet function while minimizing the risk of gastrointestinal side effects and bleeding complications.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, which are involved in the production of prostaglandins and thromboxane. This irreversible inhibition of COX is why aspirin is considered unique among antiplatelet agents.\r\n\r\nAspirin can cause exacerbation of asthma in some individuals, particularly those with aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease (AERD) or aspirin-sensitive asthma. This is a known side effect and contraindication in such cases.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 512-513, 515.","responses":[{"text":"It causes exacerbation of asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the only antiplatelet agent that irreversibly inhibits platelet function","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low dose aspirin works best when used prophylactically","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High dose aspirin works best when used prophylactically","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11701,"text":"A primigravida presents to the antenatal clinic at 10 weeks gestation for her first visit. Her blood group is B- and she has no history of abortions or miscarriages. What is the initial test that will be done?","explanation":null,"reference":"Goljan EF. Rapid Review Pathology. 5th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2019: 416.","responses":[{"text":"Husband’s blood group","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antibody titers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Direct Coomb’s test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amniocentesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect Coomb’s test","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11771,"text":"A girl is brought to the outpatient department with complaints of gum bleeding, and epistaxis. Her complete blood count (CBC) shows a normal platelet count and prolonged bleeding time. There is a family history of a younger sister with easy bruising. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"This girl with gum bleeding, epistaxis, normal platelet count, prolonged bleeding time, and a family history of a younger sister with easy bruising most likely has **Glanzmann thrombasthenia**.\r\n\r\n**Glanzmann thrombasthenia** is an inherited bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of the platelet **glycoprotein IIb/IIIa** (integrin αIIbβ3), which is essential for **platelet aggregation**. In this condition, platelets are unable to bind fibrinogen and form stable platelet plugs, leading to impaired clot formation and increased bleeding tendency.\r\n\r\nThe normal platelet count in Glanzmann thrombasthenia distinguishes it from other platelet disorders associated with thrombocytopenia. The prolonged bleeding time is a result of the defective platelet function.\r\n\r\nThe family history of a younger sister with easy bruising suggests an inherited condition. Glanzmann thrombasthenia is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning both parents are carriers of the mutated gene.\r\n\r\nThe other answer choices listed, such as drug-induced thrombocytopenia, hemophilia, immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP), and vitamin K deficiency, do not correlate with the presented clinical features and family history.","reference":"(1) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 434.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 660.","responses":[{"text":"Glanzmann thrombasthenia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug induced thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14794,"text":"Which of the following is the most correct statement regarding an allograft?","explanation":"An **allograft** refers to the transplantation of an organ or tissue from **one individual to another**, typically from a donor to a recipient. When organs or tissues are transplanted between different individuals of the same species, it is referred to as an allograft.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe successful positioning of a graft does not address the nature of the graft itself.\r\n\r\nA xenograft involves grafting between different species.\r\n\r\nAllografts can also be placed in their normal anatomical positions.\r\n\r\nAn autograft involves taking a graft from the same individual and transplanting it elsewhere in their body.","reference":"O’Connell, P. Ronan, et al., editors. Bailey \u0026 Love’s Short Practice of Surgery. 28th ed., CRC Press, Taylor \u0026 Francis Group, 2023: 1620.","responses":[{"text":"A graft performed between different species","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A graft placed in its normal position","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An organ or tissue transplanted from one individual to another","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A graft placed in a site different from that where the organ is normally located","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A graft taken from the same individual","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":17838,"text":"Which of the following is the mechanism of action of alteplase?","explanation":"Plasmin is a natural enzyme in the body that plays a vital role in breaking down fibrin, a major component of blood clots. When administered, **alteplase specifically targets and activates plasminogen, converting it into plasmin.** Plasmin then acts as a proteolytic enzyme, breaking down the fibrin mesh within blood clots, effectively dissolving them. This process is known as thrombolysis, and it helps restore blood flow in situations where there is a clot blocking an artery or vein.\r\n\r\nUnlike other medications that inhibit clot formation, alteplase works to actively dissolve existing clots. This makes it a valuable treatment option in conditions such as acute myocardial infarction (heart attack), ischemic stroke, and pulmonary embolism, where rapid clot dissolution can be life-saving. It should be administered under careful medical supervision due to its potent thrombolytic effects.","reference":"Whalen K, Finkel R, Panavelil TA. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 6th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2015: 306.","responses":[{"text":"Activates tissue plasminogen to plasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of glycoprotein IIb/IIIa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits coagulation factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Causes vasodilation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreases cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a